    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-11-23T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-11-23T11:00:00-05:00" n="266"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d266">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 656.119/184</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-11-23T16:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 23, 1917, 4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received November 24, 5.40 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>7787. Your unnumbered despatch [<hi rend="italic">telegram No. 5860</hi>] of
                    November 20 for <persName corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_HEM1">House</persName>
                    was delivered to him on the eve of his departure for France. He asked me to take
                    subject up with the British Government and answer. Mr. <persName
                        corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_BAJ1">Balfour</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_CLR1">Lord Robert Cecil</persName> think that
                    requisitioning the Dutch ships would cause irritation in Holland but neither
                    they nor the military and naval authorities have the least fear that it would
                    drive the Dutch into war against us. One of several strong reasons why they
                    would not join Germany is the certainty that they would lose their colonies.
                    …</p>
                <p>A Dutch commission is now here discussing with <persName
                        corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_CLR1">Lord Robert Cecil</persName> the whole
                    relations of Holland to the Entente powers. <persName
                        corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_CLR1">Cecil</persName> makes the suggestion
                    that if we decide to requisition the Dutch ships in American ports we refrain
                    from making a dramatic seizure of them all at once. If a small number of them be
                    requisitioned with the best understanding that can be made with the shipowners,
                    the Dutch Government will be easier to deal with thereafter. This was the
                    general plan followed by the British with Norway. The success of it in <persName
                        corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_CLR1">Cecil</persName>’s opinion will depend on
                    the secrecy with which it be done. Complete secrecy will greatly lessen Dutch
                    humiliation and irritation and is here regarded as absolutely necessary. If you
                    decide to requisition these ships the irritation would be softened by the
                    exportation to Holland of certain well-chosen commodities.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>[For a letter from the Commercial Adviser of the British Embassy, received
                        November 30, 1917, urging that negotiations with the Netherlands be
                        conducted in London and discussing the questions involved, see <hi
                            rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1078">page 1078</ref>.]</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
